<a name="0">[0]</a> <a href="#0" id=0>As our daily lives involve ever more sophisticated computers, we will find that ascribing little thoughts to machines will be increasingly useful in understanding how to get the most good out of them.</a>
<a name="1">[1]</a> <a href="#1" id=1>Much that we'll need to know concerns the information stored in computers, which is why we find ourselves using psychological words like 'knows', 'thinks', and 'wants' in referring to machines, even though machines are very different from humans and these words arose from the human need to talk about other humans.</a>
<a name="2">[2]</a> <a href="#2" id=2>As we interact more and more with computers -- both personal computers and others -- the questions of whether machines can think and what kind of thoughts they can have become ever more pertinent.</a>
<a name="3">[3]</a> <a href="#3" id=3>Few of us know much about how the electric light system or the telephone system work internally.</a>
<a name="4">[4]</a> <a href="#4" id=4>It won't be necessary for most people to know very much about how they work internally, but what we will have to know about them in order to use them is more complex than what we need to know about electric lights and telephones.</a>
